TY  - JOUR
T1  - Two-Tier Wage Structures: Implications for Equity Theory
AU  - Martin, James E.
AU  - Peterson, Melanie M.
Y1  - 1987/06/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256275
DO  - 10.5465/256275
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 297
EP  - 315
VL  - 30
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study is an application of equity theory to an examination of the effects of implementing a two-tier wage structure. Using data from 1,935 employees in retail stores, we assessed commitment to union and employer, perceived pay equity, and the union's perceived instrumentality regarding pay. Significant multivariate and univariate differences emerged for wage tier, part- or full-time status, and?among low-tier employees?work location. Results generally suggest that equity theory appears as a useful conceptual framework for examining two-tier wage structures.
AB  - This study is an application of equity theory to an examination of the effects of implementing a two-tier wage structure. Using data from 1,935 employees in retail stores, we assessed commitment to union and employer, perceived pay equity, and the union's perceived instrumentality regarding pay. Significant multivariate and univariate differences emerged for wage tier, part- or full-time status, and?among low-tier employees?work location. Results generally suggest that equity theory appears as a useful conceptual framework for examining two-tier wage structures.
